#Calculate the TOA Irradiance/Influx 
era5_land_ds = tf.convert_to_radians(era5_land_ds)
era5_land_ds = tf.calc_day_of_year(era5_land_ds)
era5_land_ds = tf.calc_eccentricty_correlation_factor(era5_land_ds)
era5_land_ds = tf.calc_hour_angle(era5_land_ds)
era5_land_ds = tf.calc_solar_declination_angle(era5_land_ds)
era5_land_ds = tf.calc_solar_zenith_angle(era5_land_ds)

#This will add the instantaneous/incident TOA influx at that timestamp. So it is in W/m^2.
ra5_land_ds = tf.calc_toa_incident_shortwave(era5_land_ds)

#To get the total influx in the hour, we multiply it by 3600 seconds (1 hour). Result is in J/m^2. 
era5_land_ds["toa_influx_hourly"] = era5_land_ds["toa_influx"] * 3600

Validation and Sanity Checks

Here are the list of EDA and checks that I wanted to do to test the functions that I implemented in src/toa_functions.py

Surface checks
  1. Plot the calculated toa_influx on the map. It should look physically reasonable, such as no weird banding, missing values, negative values.

Example of wrong would be like below. Clearly something is wrong here since there are negative values and the TOA influx is similar across the latitude.

Sanity Check
  1. Does the spatial and temporal aspects make sense? Do we see irradiance growing in the morning, peaking at noon, declining in the afternoon and none at night?
Comparison check.
  1. On aggregate, the values of the toa_influx from both datasets must agree with each other
  2. For a chosen latitude and longitude, the hourly toa_influx in ERA5_Land should match the TISR in ERA5.
Statistical checks
  1. Use statistical metrics such as nrmse, nmae, correlation, etc to compare the predicted value with the baseline for each grid cell across the year.
Unit testing
  1. Test each function and check the resultant value to see if it matches logical/physical values. This is already implemented in the unit tests files.
  2. Select a particular latitude, longitude and time and see if it matches online resources:

I was also curious to see which regions have more irradiance in different periods of the year.

It seems like April to September 2022 see more irradiance on the northern parts.

And October to March 2022 have more irradiance in the southern regions.

This trend seems to coincide with the monsoon periods in Malaysia. But this is Top-of-atmosphere irradiance which is unaffected by monsoon wind patterns below the atmosphere. This can be simply be explained by the seasonal movement of the sun and not by the monsoon season.

utc = pytz.UTC

def utc_to_kl_formatter(x, pos):
    """Format ticks: convert UTC  KL, then display."""
    dt_utc = mdates.num2date(x).replace(tzinfo=utc)
    dt_kl = dt_utc.astimezone(kl)
    return dt_kl.strftime('%Y-%m-%d %H:%M')

The graph look like this is because the TOA influx is for the next hour.

The ERA5 TISR is the accummulation of the total influx for the past hour. So TISR at: 8am is the total irradiation from 7am to 8am.

The ERA5_Land computation is for the next hour. So TOA_Influx at: 8am is the total irradiation from 8am to 9am.

This is why the ERA5 TOA curve looks right shifted.

A limitation is that we assume that the sun-Earth geometry is fixed at each hourly interval, which is not the case since the SZA, SDA, etc do change. But from above, this approximation produces neglible errors.

Statistical checks

  1. Use statistical metrics such as nrmse, nmae, correlation, etc to compare the predicted value with the baseline for each grid cell across the year.

This is to provide a numerical measurement of agreement between the 2 entire datasets across all grid cells and time. To do this, we need to align the different resolution cells of the 2 datasets. There is some options, but I chose reindexing since I want to conform the ERA5_Land dataset to the ERA5 coordinates.

The resulting plots above is what I intend to calculate the statisical values for.

We will flatten the full lat/long/time arrays into a flat array, to produce a global metric across the entire dataset.

In[]:
# 1. Create the mask to compare only matching lat/long values
valid_mask = (~np.isnan(era5_data_clipped).any(dim='valid_time')) & \
             (~np.isnan(era5_land_reindexed).any(dim='valid_time'))

# 2. Apply mask to select only valid lat/lon points (keeps all times)
x_valid = era5_data_clipped.where(valid_mask)
y_valid = era5_land_reindexed.where(valid_mask)

# 3. Flatten arrays over all dimensions for metric calculation
x_flat = x_valid.values.flatten()
y_flat = y_valid.values.flatten()

# 4. Remove any remaining NaNs
mask = ~np.isnan(x_flat) & ~np.isnan(y_flat)
x_flat = x_flat[mask]
y_flat = y_flat[mask]

# 5. Compute metrics
def rmse(a, b):
    return np.sqrt(np.mean((a - b)**2))

def mbe(a, b):
    return np.mean(a - b)

def mae(a, b):
    return np.mean(np.abs(a - b))

def nrmse(a, b):
    return rmse(a, b) / (np.max(a) - np.min(a))

def nmae(a, b):
    return mae(a, b) / (np.max(a) - np.min(a))

def correlation(a, b):
    return np.corrcoef(a, b)[0, 1]

print("RMSE:", rmse(x_flat, y_flat))
print("MBE:", mbe(x_flat, y_flat))
print("MAE:", mae(x_flat, y_flat))
print("NRMSE:", nrmse(x_flat, y_flat))
print("NMAE:", nmae(x_flat, y_flat))
print("R:", correlation(x_flat, y_flat))

RMSE: 302553.81473876664
MBE: 3144.265368234472
MAE: 195104.71146356905
NRMSE: 0.061466692956614596
NMAE: 0.03963738287112555
R: 0.9859437132820416

  • The RMSE and MAE values are small relative to the typical daily TOA peak (~4510 J/m).
    This indicates that absolute deviations remain modest.

  • MBE is close to zero (relative to the magnitude of the data). The peak TOA value is 4 to 5 million J/m while this is around 3144 J/m which is less than 1%. This means the method does not introduce any meaningful systematic biasno consistent overprediction or underprediction.

  • NRMSE (~6%) and NMAE (~4%) are well within the acceptable range for climate-physics variables, especially when comparing datasets with slightly different handling of solar accumulation windows.

  • Correlation (R 0.986) is extremely high, confirming that the temporal patternssunrise timing, peak irradiance, seasonal behaviourare captured almost perfectly.
    This is expected, since TOA geometry is deterministic, but it provides strong validation that the implementation is correct.
